<DIV dir=3Dltr id=3Dmw-content-text lang=3Den class=3Dmw-content-ltr>
<P>The <B>Secure Hash Algorithm</B> is a family of <A=20
title=3D"Cryptographic hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_hash_function">cryptog=
raphic=20
hash functions</A> published by the <A=20
title=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_=
Technology">National=20
Institute of Standards and Technology</A> (NIST) as a <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"United States of America"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_of_America">U.S.</A> =
<A=20
title=3D"Federal Information Processing Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing_Stand=
ard">Federal=20
Information Processing Standard</A> (FIPS), and may refer to:-</P>
<UL>
  <LI><B><A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DSHA-0=20
  href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-0">SHA-0</A></B>: A retronym =
applied to=20
  the original version of the 160-bit hash function published in 1993 =
under the=20
  name "SHA". It was withdrawn shortly after publication due to an =
undisclosed=20
  "significant flaw" and replaced by the slightly revised version =
SHA-1.</LI>
  <LI><B><A title=3DSHA-1 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A></B>:=20
  A 160-bit hash function which resembles the earlier MD5 algorithm. =
This was=20
  designed by the National Security Agency (NSA) to be part of the =
Digital=20
  Signature Algorithm. Cryptographic weaknesses were discovered in =
SHA-1, and=20
  the standard was no longer approved for most cryptographic uses after=20
  2010.</LI>
  <LI><B><A title=3DSHA-2 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A></B>:=20
  A family of two similar hash functions, with different block sizes, =
known as=20
  SHA-256 and SHA-512. They differ in the word size; SHA-256 uses 32-bit =
words=20
  where SHA-512 uses 64-bit words. There are also truncated versions of =
each=20
  standardized, known as SHA-224 and SHA-384. These were also designed =
by the=20
  NSA.</LI>
  <LI><B><A title=3DSHA-3 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-3">SHA-3</A></B>:=20
  A hash function formerly called Keccak, chosen in 2012 after a public=20
  competition among non-NSA designers. It supports the same hash lengths =
as=20
  SHA-2, and its internal structure differs significantly from the rest =
of the=20
  SHA family.</LI></UL>
<P>The corresponding standards are <A=20
title=3D"Federal Information Processing Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing_Stand=
ard">FIPS</A>=20
PUB 180 (original SHA), FIPS PUB 180-1 (SHA-1), FIPS PUB 180-2 (SHA-1, =
SHA-256,=20
SHA-384, and SHA-512). NIST has <A class=3D"external text"=20
href=3D"http://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/ir/2012/NIST.IR.7896.pdf"=20
rel=3Dnofollow>said</A> that FIPS 180-5 will include SHA-3.</P>
